note:
In this episode the warrior receives a call to uphold the ethics of his social standing by acting with its virtues. He must choose between his king and his dream-sent wife. This Call episode provides a thematic paradigm that structures most of the action depicted in this epic. Ethical knowledge associated with particular institutions motivates and is articulated by events. The warrior's self-knowledge makes his body an instrument of the state as it reverberates with the king's drummed summons (117.1). Nyakandaalo uses wifely knowledge to try to keep him home, he suspects (136.1). The status of the couple's union outside clan is underlined by Nyakandaalo's lack of "storage sack and seeds" (121), which accompany a clan-sanctioned bride to her new home. It is also underlined by their symmetrical address of one another, "dear one" answered by "yes, dear one" (146). These constitute the thematic building blocks of the epic:

-two kinds of knowledge: that of the self (<i>okw'-emanya</i>), which binds one to the ethics of a role (the warrior's intuition of his duty); and that of the other (<i>oku-manya</i>), which empowers one to understand and/or manipulate (Nyakandaalo's augury/ artifice); 

-institutional bases for knowledge: state (the king's summons), clan (by negative implication), and a romantic place outside of clan (marked by symmetrical address); 

-richly symbolic speech: symmetrical endearments and poetic praise; 

-richly symbolic codes: the royal drums; 

-bodies inscribed with institutional meanings: the warrior's resonant response. 

These thematic dimensions underlie most episodes, creating coherent and recurring patterns of significance in the work as a whole.
